<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-640-644  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 640 644.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Sept 11 1989 v6 n36 p35(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DCS boosts database, printer support in dbPublisher upgrade.andO;(Digital Composition Systems dbPublisher 2.0) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Picarille, Lisa.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Digital Composition Systems introduces dbPublisher 2.0, a $695upgrade of its database-publishing software that includes supportfor additional databases and printers and new predefinedtemplates.andP;  It combines database, desktop-publishing, andspreadsheet report-generation features to give users direct accessto multiple spreadsheet, word-processing, and graphics files.andP;  Theuser can then format the files into a report or document.andP;  A 'hotlink' feature automatically updates the documents to reflectchanges in the database.andP;  Version 2.0 adds support for BorlandInternational Inc's Paradox, Oracle Corp's Professional Oracle PCand Oracle OS/2, and NEC, Panasonic, and HP LaserJet IID printers.andO;It continues to support Ashton-Tate's dBASE, Nantucket's Clipper,Fox Software Inc's FoxBase, and most popular spreadsheets, alongwith PostScript and LaserJet Plus printers.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Composition Systems Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   dbPublisher 2.0 (Computer program) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Desktop publishingSoftware PackagesData base management systemsReport Generators.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Lisa PicarilleandM;Digital Composition Systems (DCS) has beefed up its database-publishingsoftware with support for additional databases and printers and new,predefined templates -- while shoehorning the upgrade into 20K bytes lessmemory.andM;Version 2.0 of dbPublisher mixes database, spreadsheet report-generation anddesktop-publishing features to give users direct access to an unlimitednumber of dissimilar databases, spreadsheets, word-processing and graphicsfiles.andP;  These files can then be formatted into a document or a report,according to Susan Dockeray, vice president of marketing for the Phoenix,Ariz., company.andM;For documents such as catalogs, form letters, phone directories and financialreports that require updating on a regular basis, a &quot;hot link&quot; featureautomatically updates the documents to reflect changes made to the database,Dockeray said.andM;dbPublisher 2.0 has added support for Borland International Inc.'s Paradox2.0 and 3.0 database software, as well as for Oracle Corp.'s ProfessionalOracle PC database and Oracle OS/2, she said.andM;Like the earlier version, dbPublisher 2.0 supports Ashton-Tate's dBASE II,III, III Plus and IV; Microrim Inc.'s R:base; Nantucket Corp.'s Clipper; FoxSoftware Inc.'s FoxBase; and Wordtech Systems Inc.'s Quicksilver.andM;To help users create documents more easily, DCS has added to version 2.0 the20 Minute Quick Start Series, a module that includes templates for mailinglabels, form letters, catalogs and price lists, according to Dockeray.andM;The software also enables users to import data from most popular spreadsheetsand word processors, including Lotus Development Corp.'s Lotus 1-2-3 andMicrosoft Corp.'s Word.andM;The program's desktop-publishing features, such as automatic pagination,hyphenation and word wrap, what-you-see-is-what-you-get page preview andautomatic reformatting of tables, allow users to design their own formats fordocuments.andM;Printer SupportandM;In addition, dbPublisher has added NEC Information Systems Inc.'s LC890,Panasonic Industrial Co.'s KX-P4450 and Hewlett-Packard Co.'s LaserJet IID tothe list of printers that it supports.andP;  They join PostScript printers, AppleComputer Inc.'s LaserWriter and LaserWriter Plus, and Hewlett-Packard'sLaserJet Plus and Series II.andM;In spite of the wealth of new features, DCS has trimmed down dbPublisher'smemory requirements from 570K bytes to 520K bytes by tightening up the codein the package.andM;Several early users of version 2.0 said that they are considering the programas an alternative to forms-generation software.andM;&quot;dbPublisher can generate the same types of output that a forms-processingproduct does,&quot; said an analyst at a large airline who beta-tested version2.0.andP;  The airline is using the program to access reservation records on amainframe to produce itineraries, said the analyst, who requested anonymity.andM;The $695 package is available now from DCS; version 1.0 users can upgrade forfree.andM;Contact Digital Composition Systems at (602) 870-7667.andO;</TEXT></DOC>